      "statement": "Magnetoelastic coupling provides the fundamental physical mechanism linking mechanical strain to magnetic properties in two-dimensional materials. Strain-induced symmetry breaking modulates magnetic anisotropy and exchange interactions, with local curvature generating or modifying the Dzyaloshinskii-Moriya interaction and other anisotropic exchange terms in the spin Hamiltonian. First-principles calculations demonstrate that approximately -3.5% compressive strain in Janus CrSeTe single-layers can make the Dzyaloshinskii-Moriya interaction dominant over Heisenberg coupling, providing a quantitative pathway to engineer chiral spin states.",
